$CATEGORY: CIT/P2/week-2/2.1-conditionals

::q1:: When a single `if` statement's condition evaluates to `False`, what happens? {
~It runs the indented block once and then re-checks the condition before moving on.#No ‚Äî an `if` is not a loop; it never re-checks or repeats its own block.
~It raises an error, because in Python every `if` must be paired with an `else`.#No ‚Äî `else` is optional; a bare `if` with no `else` is perfectly valid.
=It skips the indented block entirely and continues at the next unindented line.#Correct ‚Äî a `False` condition means the block is skipped and execution falls through.
~It runs the indented block anyway but silently discards whatever the block produced.#No ‚Äî the block does not run at all when the condition is `False`.
#### Tests the core behaviour of a lone `if` when its condition is false (corpus ¬ß5.1).
}

::q2:: In an `if`/`elif`/`else` chain, how many branches run during one execution? {
=Exactly one ‚Äî Python runs the first branch whose condition is True and skips the rest.#Correct ‚Äî evaluation stops at the first True branch; only that block executes.
~Every branch whose condition is True, evaluated one after another from the top down.#No ‚Äî later branches are never reached once an earlier one matches, even if also True.
~At most two ‚Äî the first matching branch plus the final `else` always run together.#No ‚Äî the `else` only runs when no earlier condition matched, never alongside one.
~None of them at all, unless a closing `else` is present to guarantee a branch runs.#No ‚Äî an `if`/`elif` can match and run with no `else` present at all.
#### Tests that exactly one branch executes in a chain (corpus ¬ß5.4).
}

::q3:: Why does indentation matter for the body of a Python `if` statement? {
~It is a cosmetic convention that improves readability but has no effect on behaviour.#No ‚Äî in Python indentation is grammar, not decoration; it changes what runs.
~It replaces the colon on the header line whenever the block holds a single statement.#No ‚Äî the header colon is always required; indentation is separate from it.
~It is required only inside functions, so plain `if` blocks may be left unindented.#No ‚Äî every `if` block needs consistent indentation regardless of context.
=It defines which statements belong to the branch; wrong indentation changes meaning or errors.#Correct ‚Äî indentation is the block structure, and mixing it raises an IndentationError.
#### Tests indentation as block structure, not style (corpus ¬ß5.2).
}

::q4:: The condition `age \>\= 18 and has_ticket` is True in exactly which situation? {
~When either the age is at least 18 or `has_ticket` is True, with just one side needed.#No ‚Äî that describes `or`; `and` demands both sides, not just one.
=Only when the age is at least 18 and `has_ticket` is True at the very same time.#Correct ‚Äî `and` is True only when both operands are True together.
~Whenever the age is at least 18, no matter what value `has_ticket` currently holds.#No ‚Äî `has_ticket` must also be True; ignoring it would make the `and` pointless.
~Whenever at least one of the two comparisons happens to evaluate to True on its own.#No ‚Äî "at least one" is the meaning of `or`, not of `and`.
#### Tests the meaning of `and` versus `or` (corpus ¬ß5.5).
}

::q5:: Per the corpus, when should two nested `if`s be flattened into one condition joined with `and`? {
~Always, because nesting deeper than one level automatically produces an IndentationError.#No ‚Äî deeper nesting is legal; it hurts readability but is not an error.
~Never, since combining the two tests with `and` would change the program's actual result.#No ‚Äî for "both required," the flattened `and` form gives the identical result.
~Only when the inner `if` also carries its own `else` that produces a distinct outcome.#No ‚Äî that is exactly the case to KEEP as nesting, not to flatten.
=When both conditions are simply required together and the inner `if` has no separate else.#Correct ‚Äî "both must be true" flattens cleanly; keep nesting only for diverging branches.
#### Tests judging nesting versus flattening for readability (corpus ¬ß5.6).
}

::q6:: Which line correctly rewrites the `if`/`else` that sets `status` as a conditional expression? {
=status \= "adult" if age \>\= 18 else "minor"#Correct ‚Äî the shape is value_if_true if condition else value_if_false.
~status \= if age \>\= 18 "adult" else "minor"#No ‚Äî `if` does not lead the expression form; the true-value comes first.
~status \= "adult" if age \>\= 18 elif "minor"#No ‚Äî a conditional expression uses `else`, never `elif`.
~status \= age \>\= 18 ? "adult" \: "minor"#No ‚Äî the `? \:` ternary is C-style syntax; Python uses `if`/`else` words.
#### Tests the correct syntax of the conditional (ternary) expression (corpus ¬ß5.7).
}

::q7:: Given the chain (`\>\= 90` A, `\>\= 80` B, `\>\= 70` C, else Below C), what prints for `grade \= 85`, and why? {
~"C", because 85 is greater than 70 and that comparison is the one checked first.#No ‚Äî the `\>\= 90` and `\>\= 80` tests are checked before `\>\= 70`.
~Both "B" and "C", since 85 satisfies both the `\>\= 80` and the `\>\= 70` tests.#No ‚Äî only the first True branch runs; C is never reached after B matches.
=Prints "B", because Python stops at the first True branch and 85 meets `\>\= 80`.#Correct ‚Äî 85 fails `\>\= 90`, matches `\>\= 80`, so B prints and the rest are skipped.
~"Below C", because 85 does not exactly equal any of the listed threshold numbers.#No ‚Äî the tests use `\>\=`, not equality, so 85 matches the `\>\= 80` branch.
#### Tests order-dependence and first-True-wins in a range chain (corpus ¬ß5.4).
}

::q8:: For `if temperature \< 0 or temperature \> 35\:`, which value makes the warning print? {
~temperature \= 20, because 20 sits comfortably between the two listed limit values.#No ‚Äî 20 is neither below 0 nor above 35, so neither side of the `or` is True.
=temperature \= -4, because it satisfies the `temperature \< 0` side of the `or`.#Correct ‚Äî `or` needs only one True side, and -4 is below 0.
~It prints only when both `temperature \< 0` and `temperature \> 35` are True together.#No ‚Äî that is `and`; `or` needs just one side to be True.
~temperature \= 35, because 35 counts as greater than or equal to the upper limit.#No ‚Äî the test is `\> 35` (strictly greater), and 35 is not greater than 35.
#### Tests `or` semantics and strict comparison boundaries (corpus ¬ß5.5).
}

::q9:: What lets a conditional expression sit inside `print(...)` while a plain `if`/`else` statement cannot? {
~The conditional expression runs faster, so `print` is willing to accept it as an argument.#No ‚Äî speed is irrelevant; the difference is statement versus expression.
~`print` automatically converts any `if` statement it is handed into a returned string value.#No ‚Äî `print` does no such conversion; a statement is simply not an expression.
~A statement returns `None`, which `print` then formats into the chosen branch's text.#No ‚Äî a statement does not return a usable value at all; it is not an argument.
=A conditional expression evaluates to a value, whereas an `if`/`else` statement does not.#Correct ‚Äî expressions produce values usable anywhere a value is expected; statements do not.
#### Tests the statement-versus-expression distinction (corpus ¬ß5.7).
}

::q10:: Which single line is equivalent to an outer `if logged_in\:` wrapping an inner `if is_admin\:` (no elses)? {
=if logged_in and is_admin\:#Correct ‚Äî both must be True, so `and` flattens the two nested tests exactly.
~if logged_in or is_admin\:#No ‚Äî `or` runs when either is True, changing the logic entirely.
~if not logged_in and is_admin\:#No ‚Äî `not` inverts `logged_in`, reversing the intended condition.
~if logged_in \=\= is_admin\:#No ‚Äî this tests whether the two booleans are equal, not whether both are True.
#### Tests flattening "both must be true" nesting with `and` (corpus ¬ß5.6).
}

::q11:: Mixing or forgetting the indentation of a block in Python raises an ____ (the specific error name). {
=IndentationError
=Indentation Error
=indentationerror
}

::q12:: The keyword that adds another condition between `if` and `else`, short for "else if", is ____. {
=elif
}

::q13:: Complete the conditional-expression shape\: value_if_true if condition ____ value_if_false (one keyword). {
=else
}
